                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d278">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94/637: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Mexico (<persName corresp="#p_GJC1" type="to"
                        >Clark</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-08T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 8, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>27. Your 35, February 6, 3 p.m.<note n="88" xml:id="d278fn88">Not printed.</note>
                    When a suitable opportunity offers you may express informally to the Minister
                    for Foreign Affairs the appreciation of the President and myself for the
                    assurance on the part of the Mexican Government that in case of difficulties
                    between the United States and Japan, Mexico would neither directly nor
                    indirectly be allied or associated with Japan. A similar appropriate expression
                    of appreciation may be informally conveyed by you to the Minister of War. You
                    will understand that no publicity for such a message should emanate from any
                    source.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
